Former Army Corporal Frank W. Buckles, the last surviving American veteran of World War I and the oldest known World War I era veteran in the world, has passed away at the age of 110. Buckles was a decorated soldier in the Great War and also survived more than three years in Japanese prisoner of war camps during the Second World War. He lived an exemplary life, returning home after the war, continuing his education, starting a career, and raising a family. Buckles served as the Honorary Chairman of the World War I Memorial Foundation until his passing. The President emphasizes the importance of serving veterans and their families, just as they have served the nation. The President, along with others who knew and loved Buckles, celebrates his remarkable life and recognizes the true meaning of patriotism and our obligations to each other as Americans.